WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.200
I'm John Harmon.

00:00:09.200 --> 00:00:15.360
I'm a senior data scientist at Macmillan Learning, and today I'm going to talk to you about mentoring

00:00:15.360 --> 00:00:19.799
at the R4DS Online Learning Community.

00:00:19.799 --> 00:00:25.160
So the takeaways I want you to get from this talk are that teaching is a good way to increase

00:00:25.160 --> 00:00:33.680
your fluency, and that I need 40 of you to go to r4ds.online, click Slack, and message

00:00:33.680 --> 00:00:36.880
me, JohnTheGeek.

00:00:36.880 --> 00:00:43.400
So R4DS Online Learning Community was founded in 2017 by Jesse Mostapak.

00:00:43.400 --> 00:00:49.799
It started as a study group for going through the R for Data Science book by Hadley and

00:00:50.799 --> 00:00:56.480
And it's kind of evolved into just a place you can come when you're struggling with something

00:00:56.480 --> 00:01:01.320
in R, and someone will help you figure out how to do that thing.

00:01:01.320 --> 00:01:05.360
You can find us at r4ds.online, click Slack.

00:01:05.360 --> 00:01:12.440
We have over 4,000 members, about 250 of which are active every week, and we're most famous

00:01:12.440 --> 00:01:18.879
for the Tidy Tuesday project on Twitter, where every Monday we release a data set, and then

00:01:18.879 --> 00:01:26.599
people create visualizations and post their visualizations and their code on Twitter.

00:01:26.599 --> 00:01:32.879
We also do the RFeedback Friday hashtag and the Function Friday hashtag, just as a way

00:01:32.879 --> 00:01:36.639
to engage with the RStats community on Twitter.

00:01:36.639 --> 00:01:41.940
But what I'm focusing on today is we also do office hours.

00:01:41.940 --> 00:01:50.300
Every Saturday I am on R Slack from starting at 11 a.m. Central Time, 9 a.m. Pacific, and

00:01:50.300 --> 00:01:54.500
just when questions come in, I help people find the answers.

00:01:54.500 --> 00:01:58.779
Now usually it's something like, hey, is there a function to do this?

00:01:58.779 --> 00:02:03.500
And I know what function it is, or I can go look up what function it is.

00:02:03.500 --> 00:02:07.419
But sometimes it'll be something that I have no idea, but I have more experience using

00:02:07.419 --> 00:02:12.059
R and I know how to read help and I know how to Google, and so usually I'm guiding

00:02:12.059 --> 00:02:15.419
people through how to do that.

00:02:15.419 --> 00:02:20.300
My goal, why I said I need 40 people, is I want to have 40 people doing this.

00:02:20.300 --> 00:02:24.139
We've got, I think we're up to eight now.

00:02:24.139 --> 00:02:29.880
I want to have a full-time tutor by this time next year, equivalent, so 40 hours a week.

00:02:29.880 --> 00:02:31.940
More than that would be great.

00:02:31.940 --> 00:02:38.979
So I would like you to go to r4ds.online, click Slack, and message John the Geek.

00:02:38.979 --> 00:02:40.979
Some examples of why you should do this.

00:02:40.979 --> 00:02:45.460
Number one, teaching is a great way to learn.

00:02:45.460 --> 00:02:53.179
When you teach something, you have to understand it, and so it helps you develop more proficiency.

00:02:53.179 --> 00:02:56.380
There's some references on that in the learning by teaching article on Wikipedia.

00:02:56.380 --> 00:03:00.500
I don't have time to go through all of that, but it's there.

00:03:00.500 --> 00:03:01.699
Some examples.

00:03:01.699 --> 00:03:10.339
Over on the left was just last week, someone was asking about how to learn to do presentations

00:03:10.339 --> 00:03:16.179
with RMD, and this was really helpful to me.

00:03:16.179 --> 00:03:21.619
Not quite timely enough, because if you look at my slides, this is in Google Slides, but

00:03:21.619 --> 00:03:30.259
soon, now I have the info that I know where to go to learn how to make these presentations

00:03:30.259 --> 00:03:37.860
in R. Another example was when Toon from Tidy Models first came out on GitHub, a bunch of

00:03:37.860 --> 00:03:43.059
us were playing with that, and someone was like, hey, this example code in the vignette

00:03:43.059 --> 00:03:47.660
doesn't work, and so I was like, oh, let me look, and oh, it didn't work for me either,

00:03:47.660 --> 00:03:55.220
so I ended up creating an issue, worked through that with Max, and then I also did a pull

00:03:55.220 --> 00:04:00.059
request for some documentation, so I ended up, I'm a contributor to Toon now because

00:04:00.059 --> 00:04:06.419
of R4DS, and also, I learned a lot about how Toon works by going through trying to figure

00:04:06.419 --> 00:04:11.020
out why it didn't work and then realizing, oh, because it's broken.

00:04:11.020 --> 00:04:17.619
So if you want to see more examples, you can go to r4ds.online, you can click Slack, and

00:04:17.619 --> 00:04:22.980
hopefully message me, John the Geek, and sign up for an hour a week, an hour every

00:04:22.980 --> 00:04:27.579
other week, an hour a month, whatever you can do.

00:04:27.579 --> 00:04:32.579
It's just, it's a lot of fun, and it's a great way to develop your skills.

00:04:32.579 --> 00:04:33.660
And that's my time.

00:04:33.660 --> 00:04:34.660
Thank you.

00:04:34.660 --> 00:04:34.660


